Part 1: Data

Since this wasnt an experiment, causal connections cannot be made here. That is, data in this study was merely observed and as such only generalisations can be made.

Part 2: Research question

Q: Can we observe an association between the imdb rating of a movie and other variables such as the length of a movie and audience polls on Rotten tomatoes?

All the registered members of IMDb can cast their votes/ratings for any movie. IMDb takes all the individual votes cast by the registered users and uses them to calculate a single rating. It is widely known that the weighted average method is used in this calculation and as such it could lead to manipulation of votes. Being able to predict the imdb rating based on historical data could be useful in checking this phenomenon.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

First, we merge the best_pic_nom and best_pic_win variables and create a new one, best_pic. Just to de-congest the dataset.

movies <- movies %>%
  mutate(best_pic = ifelse(best_pic_nom == "no" & best_pic_win == "no", "No BPEntry",
    ifelse(best_pic_nom == "yes" & best_pic_win == "no", "Lost BP",
           ifelse(best_pic_nom == "yes" & best_pic_win == "yes", "Won BP",
                  NA))))

Categorical:

  • title_type (candidate explanantory var)
  • genre (ditto)
  • mpaa_rating (ditto)
  • critics rating (ditto)
  • audience_rating (ditto)
  • best_pic (ditto)

Numerical:

  • imdb_rating (response var)

  • runtime (candidate explanantory var)
  • imdb_num_votes (ditto)
  • critics_score (ditto)

  • audience_score (ditto)

Since we can observe the lack of collinearity among the variables except for that which exists between audience score and critics score, we can conclude that all the variables can be included in the initial full model- the only caveat being that either the audience score or the critics score be picked but not both. Also, looking at the above pairwise plots, the data for imdb_num_votes is strongly right skewed. This strong skew can be taken care of by log transforming the imdb_num_votes variable for the number of observations left.

ggplot(data = movies_n, aes (x = log10(imdb_num_votes))) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.25, color='darkgray', fill  = 'darkblue') + 
  labs(title = "Distribution of Log Transformed Variable: log10(imdb_num_votes)" )

This looks much better, nearly normal.

  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of runtime Vs imdb_rating" )

There looks to be a linear relationship, albeit stronger in the second instance with the runtime variable.

Great! So as can be seen, the greatest Adjusted R-squared has been arrived at - 0.771. In conclusion, we see that the model without the inclusion of the top200_box variable seems just fine in predicting the imdb_rating.

Now, lets run diagnostics on our model just to be sure were good to go. The following would be the criteria: 1. Linear relationships between (numerical) x and y 2. Nearly normal residuals with mean 0 3. Constant variability of residuals 4. Independent residuals

ggplot(data = updated_model6, aes(x = updated_model6$residuals)) + 
  geom_histogram(color = 'darkgray', fill = 'darkblue', binwidth = 0.1)  + 
  labs(x = "residuals", title = "Distribution of Residuals using model6" )

qqnorm(updated_model6$residuals, col = 'darkblue') 
qqline(updated_model6$residuals, col = 'red')

summary(updated_model6$residuals)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -2.74301 -0.17667  0.06581  0.00000  0.28121  1.09825

From the summary statistics the mean of the residuals can be seen to equal zero. However, the histogram shows that the residuals are left skewed. A proportion of outliers is the cause of this. The Q-Q plot also indicates a nearly normal distribution, with some deviation from normality occurring on the left hand side, indicating again that the data is left skewed.

For condition 3, lets plot the residuals against the predictions.

plot(updated_model6$residuals ~ updated_model6$fitted, 
     main = 'Plot of Residuals vs Model Prediction from MLR Model', 
     xlab = 'prediction', 
     ylab = 'residuals', 
     col = 'darkblue')

The plot show that the variability of residuals is not constant. Thus, the SE, CI and hypothesis tests could be affected.. Later on, Ill look up how to fix inconsistent residuals because it could affect the accuracy of my model.

For condition 4, lets plot the residuals as they are observed in the data.

plot(updated_model6$residuals, 
     main = 'Plot of Residuals for MLR Model', 
     xlab = 'index', 
     ylab = 'residuals', 
     col = 'darkblue')

From the plot, the residuals are randomly distributed. They are therefore independent.

Part 6: Conclusion

Upon checking the imdb website, the imdb rating falls within the range of values within a 95% confidence interval - 8.4. Looking at the variability in the residuals, the confidence intervals might be shorter in width that what was used here. And with the adjusted R-squared being 0.7771, it implies that about 23% of the variability in the model remains unexplained. Addition of other unknown variables, could improve the prediction without having to narrow the CI.
